8695	  Let \(C^\bullet, C'^\bullet\) be cochain complexes in a preadditive category, with augmentation
8696	  maps \(f : Y \to C^0\) (\(f \cdot d^0 = 0\)) and \(f' : Y' \to C'^0\) (\(f' \cdot d'^0 = 0\)).
8697	  Given an isomorphism \(\varphi : C^\bullet \cong C'^\bullet\) of the base complexes, an
8698	  isomorphism \(e_Y : Y \cong Y'\) of the augmentation objects, and a compatibility square
8699	  \(f \cdot \varphi_0 = e_Y \cdot f'\) intertwining the augmentation maps through \(e_Y\) and the
8700	  degree-\(0\) component \(\varphi_0\) of \(\varphi\), there is an isomorphism of augmented
8701	  cochain complexes
8702	  \[
8703	    C^\bullet.\operatorname{augment} f \;\cong\; C'^\bullet.\operatorname{augment} f'.
8704	  \]
8705	\end{lemma}
8706	\begin{proof}
8707	  Define the isomorphism degreewise: take the degree-\(0\) component to be \(e_Y\) and the
8708	  degree-\(n+1\) component to be \(\varphi_n\), the \(n\)-th component of \(\varphi\). The
8709	  degree-\(0\) differential square is exactly the supplied compatibility square
8710	  \(f \cdot \varphi_0 = e_Y \cdot f'\). For each degree \(n+1\), the augmented differential is the
8711	  original differential of the base complex (the augmentation only modifies the bottom slot), so
8712	  the square reduces to the commutativity condition of \(\varphi\) at degree \(n\).
8713	  Hence all squares commute and the components assemble to an isomorphism.
8714	\end{proof}
